65–1310":"1265–1310","1270–1326":"1270–1326","1297":"1297","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1270":"1270","1338":"1338","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","1265":"1265","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Davenport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Davenport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Bulkeley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bulkeley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Oteworth, England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","Eaton, Cheshire, England":"Eaton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bulkeley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Cheshire named Bulkeley, from Old English <i>bulluc</i> ‘bullock’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","History: Peter Bulkeley (1583–1659), Puritan divine, who came from Bedfordshire, England, was a founder of Concord, MA, in 1636."],"variants":[{"name":"Bulkley","meanings":["English (Hampshire): variant of   Bulkeley  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Sung, Jung, Yong, Chang, Kwang, Sang, Dong, Hyun, Jae, Jin, Kyung, Jong, Chong, Chung, Byung, Jeong, Pyong, Myong, Hak, Jin Hwan, Sook, Yeong, Choon.","Korean: variant of   O  .","Japanese: variant of <b>Ō</b> (see   O  )."],"variants":[{"name":"O","meanings":["(1997: 122;2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Bo Young, Chae, Chong Hwan, Dong Kun, Ho, Hwan, Hyun, Jong, Jung, Ki Soon, Kwang.  Korean Min, Chong, Chol, Jung Ho, Myong, Sa, Sung Kyun.","Korean (오; Chinese character: 吳): historically, there were two Chinese characters for the O surname, but by the late Koryŏ period (14th century  AD ), one of them had disappeared. Some records indicate that there are as many as 210 different clans for the remaining character, but only sixteen can be positively documented. All sixteen of these clans originate from the same ancestor, O Ch’ŏm (吳 瞻), who migrated to Korea from China during the reign of Shilla's King Chijŭng (500–514  AD ). <i>O</i> is a common surname throughout Korea. Compare   Oh  ."]}]},{"name":"Eaton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Eaton or Eton, such as Eaton Socon (Bedfordshire), Eaton (Cheshire), or Eton (Buckinghamshire), named from either Old English <i>ēa</i> ‘river’ or <i>ēg</i> ‘island, low-lying land’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’.","History: Nathaneal Eaton, born in Coventry, England, <i>c.</i> 1609, came to MA in 1637 and was the first head of Harvard College, in 1638–39."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":18,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":31,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":40,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Bulkeley of Eaton was born in 1297, in Eaton, Cheshire, England, his father, William de Bulkeley, was 32 and his mother, Matilda Davenport, was 27. He had at least 1 daughter with Agnes de Cholmondeley. He died in 1350, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 53."},"et":{"1297–1350":"1297–1350","1300–1338":"1300–1338","1330–Female":"1330–Surnud","1265–1310":"1265–1310","1270–1326":"1270–1326","1297":"1297","1330":"1330","1350":"1350","1270":"1270","1338":"1338","1326":"1326","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1300":"1300","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","1265":"1265","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Davenport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Davenport, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chester, Cheshire, England":"Chester, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bulkeley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bulkeley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Oteworth, England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Eaton, Cheshire